hoffollyfrom00tuch_0 }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Prime Ministers, From Sir Robert Walpole to Edward Heath |editor-link=Herbert van Thal |editor-last=Van Thal |editor-first=Herbert |year=1974 |publisher=Stein and Day |isbn=978-0-8128-1738-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/primeministersfr0000vant }}\n* {{cite book |title=Essays Political and Biographical|last=Walpole |first=S. |year=2009 |ref=Walpole |publisher=BiblioBazaar, llc |isbn=978-1-113-70982-0}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Denver, David, and Mark Garnett. \"The popularity of British prime ministers.\" ''British Journal of Politics and International Relations'' 14.1 (2012): 57-73.\n* Kaarbo, Juliet, and Margaret G. Hermann. \"Leadership styles of prime ministers: How individual differences affect the foreign policymaking process.\" ''Leadership Quarterly'' 9.3 (1998): 243-263. [http://panel.inkuba.com/sites/2/archivos/Leadership%203.pdf online]\n* King, Anthony Stephen, ed. ''The British Prime Minister'' (Duke UP, 1985).\n* Langer, Ana In\u00e9s. \"A historical exploration of the personalisation of politics in the print media: The British Prime Ministers (1945\u20131999).\" ''Parliamentary Affairs'' 60.3 (2007): 371-387.\n* {{cite book|author1=Strangio, Paul |author2=Paul 't Hart|author3=James Walter|title=Understanding Prime-Ministerial Performance: Comparative Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kMu2nAZmMbEC&pg=PA225|year=2013|publisher=Oxford UP|isbn=9780199666423}}\n* Theakston, Kevin, and Mark Gill. \"Rating 20th-century British prime ministers.\" ''British Journal of Politics and International Relations'' 8.2 (2006): 193-213.\n* Thomson, George Malcolm. ''The Prime Ministers: From Robert Walpole to Margaret Thatcher'' (Secker & Warburg, 1980)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Prime ministers of the United Kingdom}}\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/prime-ministers-office-10-downing-street#content Number 10 official website]\n* [http://www.parliament.uk Parliament of the United Kingdom website]\n* [http://www.archontology.org/nations/uk/bpm/ Principal Ministers of the Crown: 1730\u20132006]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list = \n{{Prime Minister of the United Kingdom}}\n{{List of UK Prime Ministers}}\n{{Great Offices of State}}\n{{Cabinet positions in the United Kingdom}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{UK heads of governments}}\n{{Europe heads of state and government}}\n{{United Kingdom topics}}\n{{Downing Street}}\n{{Prime Minister}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prime Minister Of The United Kingdom}}\n[[Category:British Prime Minister's Office| ]]\n[[Category:Ministerial offices in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political history of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom nuclear command and control]]\n", "name_user": "100.37.172.69", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Albert Shepherd", "text_new": "{{about||the English recipient of the Victoria Cross|Albert Edward Shepherd|the English actor|Albert Shepherd (actor)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Albert Shepherd\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1885|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Great Lever]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1929|11|8|1885|9|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Bolton]], England\n| height = \n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1901\u20131902\n| clubs1 = Bolton Temperance\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = 1902\u20131903\n| clubs2 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1903\u20131908\n| clubs3 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| caps3 = 115\n| goals3 = 85\n| years4 = 1908\u20131914\n| clubs4 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps4 = 104\n| goals4 = 76\n| years5 = 1914\u20131915\n| clubs5 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| caps5 = 22\n| goals5 = 10\n| totalcaps = 241 | totalgoals= 171\n| nationalyears1 = 1906\u2013?\n| nationalteam1 = [[The Football League XI|Football League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 1906\u20131911\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n}}\n\n'''Albert Shepherd''' (10 September 1885 \u2013 8 November 1929) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He began his career with amateur side Bolton Temperance before signing for [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] but was released a year later having made no appearances. He instead joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] side [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and was eventually handed his professional debut in 1904. Shepherd won promotion in his first full season with Bolton and the following year he finished as the top goalscorer in the First Division. His form led to call ups for the [[The Football League XI|Football League representative XI]] and the [[England national football team]], scoring on his debut for both sides in 1906.\n\nHe joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in 1908, winning the First Division title and becoming the first player for Newcastle to reach thirty goals in a single season during the 1909\u201310 season, including scoring both goals in the [[1910 FA Cup Final]] during a 2\u20130 victory over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]. He gained a second cap for England in 1911 before his career was halted after sustaining a serious knee injury that kept him out for over a year. After struggling to regain form after his return, he was sold to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] where he spent one season before retiring. During his career, he scored over 150 goals in the [[Football League]] in 241 appearances.\n\n==Early life==\nShepherd was born at 10 South Street in [[Great Lever]]. He was the third of three children of Thomas and Martha Shepherd and was baptised at St. Mark's Church on 31 March 1902. His father worked as a cotton spinner before being assigned to look after mules at a cotton mill.<ref name=\"efo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersS/BioShepherdA.html |title=Albert Shepherd |publisher=England Football Online |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Bolton Wanderers===\nShepherd was playing for local amateur club Bolton Temperance when he was offered an amateur contract with [[Football League First Division|First Division]] side [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in 1901. However, he was unable to break into the first team and was allowed to leave the club. He instead joined [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] but was allowed to play for amateur club Bolton St. Luke's in the [[Lancashire Combination]] before making his professional debut in November 1904.<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n\nIn his first full season, he scored fifteen league goals to help Bolton finish second in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] and gain promotion. He continued his scoring form in the First Division, netting 25 times as he finished as the league's top goalscorer,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DrqdAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA308&lpg=PA308&dq=albert+shepherd+bolton+wanderers&source=bl&ots=IYLOTJMhBT&sig=s9njLiV7oEn8LCQEqzEJligIy_0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiatpvKpsHaAhWEOBQKHU2BCIo4ChDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20bolton%20wanderers&f=false |title=The History of the English Football League: Part One 1888\u20131930 |publisher=Strategic Book Publishing |first=Michael J. |last= Slade |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-62516-183-3}}</ref><ref name=\"pul\">{{cite web |url=https://playupliverpool.com/1929/11/08/albert-shepherd-playupliverpool-com/ |title=Albert Shepherd |publisher=Play Up Liverpool |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> and was called up to the [[The Football League XI|Football League]] representative side for a match against their Scottish counterparts. Played at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], the match ended in a 6\u20132 victory for the English Football League with Shepherd scoring four times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/games/19060324.html |title=Sat 24 Mar 1906 English Football League 6 SFL 2 |publisher=London Hearts |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> The following month, he received his first call up for the [[England national football team|England]] squad for a match against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] on 7 April 1906.<ref name=\"efo\"/> England were reduced to ten men early in the match after [[Harry Makepeace]] was forced off with injury. Scotland took a 2\u20130 lead before Shepherd scored direct from a free-kick in the 81st minute, only the second time an English international player had scored a direct free-kick. Despite his goal, England were unable to regain a foothold in the match with Scotland winning 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1905-06/M0088Sco1906.html |title=Scotland 2\u20131 England |publisher=England Football Online |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n\nIn November 1908, [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a club record fee of \u00a3800, only \u00a3200 less than the [[Progression of the British football transfer fee record|British transfer record]] at the time. Signed as a replacement for [[Bill Appleyard]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1795578-20-best-newcastle-united-strikers-of-all-time |title=20 Best Newcastle United Strikers of All-Time |publisher=Bleacher Report |first=Dan |last=Sheridan |date=2 October 2013 |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> he made a goalscoring debut for the club during a 4\u20130 victory over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] but played in a 9\u20131 defeat to [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby|local]] rivals [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the following match, scoring Newcastle's only goal via a penalty.<ref name=\"fft\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/hats-hacks-and-hafnia-fa-cup-firsts-and-trailblazers?_format=amp |title=Hats, hacks and Hafnia: FA Cup firsts and trailblazers |work=[[FourFourTwo]] |first=Olly |last=Ricketts |date=28 May 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> He went on to finish as the club's top goalscorer with fifteen league goals in his first season, helping the club win the First Division title. The following season, he became the first Newcastle player to score more than 30 goals in a single season, reaching 31, and he repeated the feat in the 1910\u201311 season when he finished as the top scorer in the First Division.<ref name=\"Fletcher\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q7QVCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA179&lpg=PA179&dq=albert+shepherd+bolton+wanderers&source=bl&ots=uMyQj-QQOo&sig=s4Yn21_77UZez4H-xJ5cDmtbems&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjSxZH2xL_aAhVhL8AKHb6PCuM4ChDoATACegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20bolton%20wanderers&f=false |title=The Toon's 100 Greatest Players....Ever |first=Kev|last= Fletcher |publisher=Lulu.com |year=2015 |pp=179\u2013180 |isbn=978-1-326-29685-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html |title=Football League Div 1 & 2 Leading Goalscorers 1889\u20131915 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |first=James M. |last=Ross |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nShepherd scored both goals during a 2\u20130 win over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] in the replay of the [[1910 FA Cup Final]] to secure the club's first [[FA Cup]] victory. After giving Newcastle the lead with a low driving shot, he converted a penalty to become the first player to score a penalty in an FA Cup final.<ref name=\"efo\"/><ref name=\"fft\"/><ref name=\"Fletcher\"/> Newcastle reached the final again the following year, with Shepherd scoring eight times during the previous rounds and winning a second cap for England in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] on 11 February 1911.<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n\nHowever, a serious injury sustained during a collision with a goalkeeper during a match against Blackburn Rovers ruled him out of the final, which Newcastle lost 1\u20130.<ref name=\"Fletcher\"/> Contesting a loose ball with Rovers goalkeeper [[Jimmy Ashcroft]], when the pair made contact that resulted in Shepherd damaging ligaments and tearing muscles in his knee. The injury kept him out for over a year, missing the whole 1911\u201312 season and the start of the following year, and on his return he was unable to regain the goalscoring form he had shown before.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mGJsZeq7myAC&pg=PT23&lpg=PT23&dq=albert+shepherd+newcastle+united&source=bl&ots=W2Uqlme15F&sig=IRDKTGTLqPHRLlAY1uhJDWFvbJY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIvqH29MHaAhVIK8AKHTJ1C244FBDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20newcastle%20united&f=false |title=The Toon: A Complete History of Newcastle United Football Club |publisher=Random House |first=Roger |last=Hutchinson |year=2011 |isbn=1841589152}}</ref> He eventually left the club in July 1914, joining fellow First Division side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]. He scored ten league goals in twenty-two appearances before he retired from professional football following the outbreak of World War I.<ref name=\"efo\"/><ref name=\"pul\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nShepherd married Mary Ellen Harwood on 29 May 1906 in Bolton. He died on 8 November 1929 at the Crown & Cushion Inn, a pub where he was licensee, in Bolton at the age of 44, leaving \u00a3705 and 12 shillings to his wife in his will. He was buried four days later at [[Christ Church, Walmsley]] with former Bolton players [[Joe Smith (football forward, born 1889)|Joe Smith]], [[Bert Baverstock]], [[Ted Vizard]], [[Billy Jennings (Welsh footballer)|Billy Jennings]], [[George Samuel Eccles|George Eccles]] and [[Jimmy Seddon]] as [[pallbearer]]s.<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Newcastle United'''<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n* [[Football League First Division]] winner: 1908\u201309\n* [[FA Cup]] winner: 1910\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{English First Division/Premier League top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shepherd, Albert}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:First Division/Premier League top scorers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Great Lever]]\n[[Category:English Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the English recipient of the Victoria Cross|Albert Edward Shepherd|the English actor|Albert Shepherd (actor)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Albert Shepherd\n| image = \n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1885|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Great Lever]], England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1929|11|8|1885|9|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Bolton]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1901\u20131902\n| clubs1 = Bolton Temperance\n| caps1 = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = 1902\u20131903\n| clubs2 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1903\u20131908\n| clubs3 = [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]\n| caps3 = 115\n| goals3 = 85\n| years4 = 1908\u20131914\n| clubs4 = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps4 = 104\n| goals4 = 76\n| years5 = 1914\u20131915\n| clubs5 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| caps5 = 22\n| goals5 = 10\n| totalcaps = 241 | totalgoals= 171\n| nationalyears1 = 1906\u2013?\n| nationalteam1 = [[The Football League XI| Football League XI]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 4\n| nationalyears2 = 1906\u20131911\n| nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n}}\n\n'''Albert Shepherd''' (10 September 1885 \u2013 8 November 1929) was an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He began his career with amateur side Bolton Temperance before signing for [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] but was released a year later having made no appearances. He instead joined [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] side [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and was eventually handed his professional debut in 1904. Shepherd won promotion in his first full season with Bolton and the following year he finished as the top goalscorer in the First Division. His form led to call ups for the [[The Football League XI|Football League representative XI]] and the [[England national football team]], scoring on his debut for both sides in 1906.\n\nHe joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in 1908, winning the First Division title and becoming the first player for Newcastle to reach thirty goals in a single season during the 1909\u201310 season, including scoring both goals in the [[1910 FA Cup Final]] during a 2\u20130 victory over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]]. He gained a second cap for England in 1911 before his career was halted after sustaining a serious knee injury that kept him out for over a year. After struggling to regain form after his return, he was sold to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] where he spent one season before retiring. During his career, he scored over 150 goals in the [[Football League]] in 241 appearances.\n\n==Early life==\nShepherd was born at 10 South Street in [[Great Lever]]. He was the third of three children of Thomas and Martha Shepherd and was baptised at St. Mark's Church on 31 March 1902. His father worked as a cotton spinner before being assigned to look after mules at a cotton mill.<ref name=\"efo\">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersS/BioShepherdA.html |title=Albert Shepherd |publisher=England Football Online |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Bolton Wanderers===\nShepherd was playing for local amateur club Bolton Temperance when he was offered an amateur contract with [[Football League First Division|First Division]] side [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in 1901. However, he was unable to break into the first team and was allowed to leave the club. He instead joined [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] but was allowed to play for amateur club Bolton St. Luke's in the [[Lancashire Combination]] before making his professional debut in November 1904.<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n\nIn his first full season, he scored fifteen league goals to help Bolton finish second in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] and gain promotion. He continued his scoring form in the First Division, netting 25 times as he finished as the league's top goalscorer,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DrqdAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA308&lpg=PA308&dq=albert+shepherd+bolton+wanderers&source=bl&ots=IYLOTJMhBT&sig=s9njLiV7oEn8LCQEqzEJligIy_0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiatpvKpsHaAhWEOBQKHU2BCIo4ChDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20bolton%20wanderers&f=false |title=The History of the English Football League: Part One 1888\u20131930 |publisher=Strategic Book Publishing |first=Michael J. |last= Slade |year=2013 |isbn=978-1-62516-183-3}}</ref><ref name=\"pul\">{{cite web |url=https://playupliverpool.com/1929/11/08/albert-shepherd-playupliverpool-com/ |title=Albert Shepherd |publisher=Play Up Liverpool |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> and was called up to the [[The Football League XI|Football League]] representative side for a match against their Scottish counterparts. Played at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]], the match ended in a 6\u20132 victory for the English Football League with Shepherd scoring four times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/games/19060324.html |title=Sat 24 Mar 1906 English Football League 6 SFL 2 |publisher=London Hearts |accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> The following month, he received his first call up for the [[England national football team|England]] squad for a match against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] on 7 April 1906.<ref name=\"efo\"/> England were reduced to ten men early in the match after [[Harry Makepeace]] was forced off with injury. Scotland took a 2\u20130 lead before Shepherd scored direct from a free-kick in the 81st minute, only the second time an English international player had scored a direct free-kick. Despite his goal, England were unable to regain a foothold in the match with Scotland winning 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/Seas1900-39/1905-06/M0088Sco1906.html |title=Scotland 2\u20131 England |publisher=England Football Online |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n\nIn November 1908, [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a club record fee of \u00a3800, only \u00a3200 less than the [[Progression of the British football transfer fee record|British transfer record]] at the time. Signed as a replacement for [[Bill Appleyard]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1795578-20-best-newcastle-united-strikers-of-all-time |title=20 Best Newcastle United Strikers of All-Time |publisher=Bleacher Report |first=Dan |last=Sheridan |date=2 October 2013 |accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref> he made a goalscoring debut for the club during a 4\u20130 victory over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] but played in a 9\u20131 defeat to [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby|local]] rivals [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the following match, scoring Newcastle's only goal via a penalty.<ref name=\"fft\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/hats-hacks-and-hafnia-fa-cup-firsts-and-trailblazers?_format=amp |title=Hats, hacks and Hafnia: FA Cup firsts and trailblazers |work=[[FourFourTwo]] |first=Olly |last=Ricketts |date=28 May 2015 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> He went on to finish as the club's top goalscorer with fifteen league goals in his first season, helping the club win the First Division title. The following season, he became the first Newcastle player to score more than 30 goals in a single season, reaching 31, and he repeated the feat in the 1910\u201311 season when he finished as the top scorer in the First Division.<ref name=\"Fletcher\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Q7QVCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA179&lpg=PA179&dq=albert+shepherd+bolton+wanderers&source=bl&ots=uMyQj-QQOo&sig=s4Yn21_77UZez4H-xJ5cDmtbems&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjSxZH2xL_aAhVhL8AKHb6PCuM4ChDoATACegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20bolton%20wanderers&f=false |title=The Toon's 100 Greatest Players....Ever |first=Kev|last= Fletcher |publisher=Lulu.com |year=2015 |pp=179\u2013180 |isbn=978-1-326-29685-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engtops.html |title=Football League Div 1 & 2 Leading Goalscorers 1889\u20131915 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |first=James M. |last=Ross |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nShepherd scored both goals during a 2\u20130 win over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] in the replay of the [[1910 FA Cup Final]] to secure the club's first [[FA Cup]] victory. After giving Newcastle the lead with a low driving shot, he converted a penalty to become the first player to score a penalty in an FA Cup final.<ref name=\"efo\"/><ref name=\"fft\"/><ref name=\"Fletcher\"/> Newcastle reached the final again the following year, with Shepherd scoring eight times during the previous rounds and winning a second cap for England in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] on 11 February 1911.<ref name=\"efo\"/> \n\nHowever, a serious injury sustained during a collision with a goalkeeper during a match against Blackburn Rovers ruled him out of the final, which Newcastle lost 1\u20130.<ref name=\"Fletcher\"/> Contesting a loose ball with Rovers goalkeeper [[Jimmy Ashcroft]], when the pair made contact that resulted in Shepherd damaging ligaments and tearing muscles in his knee. The injury kept him out for over a year, missing the whole 1911\u201312 season and the start of the following year, and on his return he was unable to regain the goalscoring form he had shown before.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mGJsZeq7myAC&pg=PT23&lpg=PT23&dq=albert+shepherd+newcastle+united&source=bl&ots=W2Uqlme15F&sig=IRDKTGTLqPHRLlAY1uhJDWFvbJY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjIvqH29MHaAhVIK8AKHTJ1C244FBDoATABegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=albert%20shepherd%20newcastle%20united&f=false |title=The Toon: A Complete History of Newcastle United Football Club |publisher=Random House |first=Roger |last=Hutchinson |year=2011 |isbn=1841589152}}</ref> He eventually left the club in July 1914, joining fellow First Division side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]. He scored ten league goals in twenty-two appearances before he retired from professional football following the outbreak of World War I.<ref name=\"efo\"/><ref name=\"pul\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nShepherd married Mary Ellen Harwood on 29 May 1906 in Bolton. He died on 8 November 1929 at the Crown & Cushion Inn, a pub where he was licensee, in Bolton at the age of 44, leaving \u00a3705 and 12 shillings to his wife in his will. He was buried four days later at [[Christ Church, Walmsley]] with former Bolton players [[Joe Smith (football forward, born 1889)|Joe Smith]], [[Bert Baverstock]], [[Ted Vizard]], [[Billy Jennings (Welsh footballer)|Billy Jennings]], [[George Samuel Eccles|George Eccles]] and [[Jimmy Seddon]] as [[pallbearer]]s.<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n'''Newcastle United'''<ref name=\"efo\"/>\n* [[Football League First Division]] winner: 1908\u201309\n* [[FA Cup]] winner: 1910\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{English First Division/Premier League top scorers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shepherd, Albert}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bolton Wanderers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:First Division/Premier League top scorers]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n